    passage: 'Historians continue to debate the primary causes of the fall of the Roman Empire. Edward Gibbon attributed it to moral decay and the rise of Christianity. More recent scholars have emphasized economic factors, including inflation, trade disruptions, and the unsustainable cost of maintaining the military. Others point to external pressures from migrating Germanic tribes. Increasingly, historians favor a multicausal explanation, arguing that no single factor was sufficient to topple such a vast and complex civilization.',
